  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency response to floods</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">UNICEF work with displaced populations and their hosting communities to provide shared latrines, supplies and promote self-construction of latrines to construct 500 temporary emergency latrines for a population of 7,000 boys, girls, men, and women.  This modality encourages sanitation behaviors without creating camp services or dependency on full provision of services.  UNICEF will install ten  handpumps in displacement sites, train water committees to maintain and operate these facilities, and provide household water storage and collection items to provide access to water to 7,000 individuals. During the installation of the handpumps UNICEF is installing and operating an emergency water treatment unit to provide water during this period.  In parallel to these activities hygiene promotion services encourage safe hygiene behaviors through provision of disease prevention messages, household sanitation promotion, and household water treatment and storage practice promotion.

The Child Protection component under this project seeks to reach 8,000 individuals in Leer, Mayardit and Rubkona counties through family tracing and reunification (FTR), case management, strengthened referrals for unaccompanied and separated children (UASC), children associated with armed groups and forces (CAAFAG), and other vulnerable children and establishing / expansion of child friendly spaces. Mental Health and Psychosocial Services (MHPSS) are also provided to children, caregivers, and GBV survivors.</narrative>
  </description>
